SIMPLE: evict
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Evict
<hw>E*vict"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Evicted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Evicting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>evictus</ets>, p. p. of
<ets>evincere</ets> to overcome completely, evict. See
<er>Evince</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To dispossess
by a judicial process; to dispossess by paramount right or claim of such
right; to eject; to oust.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The law of England would speedily <qex>evict</qex> them out of
their possession.</q> <rj><qau>Sir. J. Davies.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To evince; to prove.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Cheyne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Eviction</ent>⟦br⟧
